# Dispatch scope (supersedes operations user id)

**On-demand rule.** Mission Control warm-up loads [`.sedea/centers/research-and-development/rules/bootstrap.mdc`](bootstrap.mdc) as the sole R&D `alwaysApply: true` bootstrap. Read **this file** when you need dispatch-scoped operations paths, phase-tagged storage contracts, or legacy CLI flags during hybrid migration — not on every dispatch warm-up.

**Filename note:** This rule file retains the legacy **`31_operations-user-id`** path until a follow-on rename PR. Content here **supersedes** agent-facing **`operationsUserId`** and **`joint`** namespace instructions.

Normative hosting layout: [`.sedea/centers/sedea/rules/0_hosting-repo.mdc`](.sedea/centers/sedea/rules/0_hosting-repo.mdc) § **Operations storage phases**, § **Dispatch bundles under `operations/`**, and § **Plans (dispatch-scoped discovery)**.

---

## Agent dispatch scope (binding)

Every Mission Control agent lane on a dispatch is bound to **one dispatch scope**:

| Field | Source | Agent use |
|-------|--------|-----------|
| **`dispatchId`** | Warm-up / spawn preamble (**Active dispatch UUID**) | Stable dispatch identity; never infer from epoch folder name alone |
| **Bundle directory** | Warm-up / spawn preamble (absolute path) | Read/write dispatch bundle artifacts **only** under this directory |
| **Slot id** | Lane identity block | Open **only** `dispatch-lane.<slotId>.v1.json` for this lane unless spawn handover names another lane file in the **same** bundle |

**Forbidden:**

- Constructing `.sedea/operations/<user-id>/...` or `.sedea/operations/joint/...` paths for lane work
- Cross-reading **`parent-child-registry.v1.json`**, **`dispatch-tab.v1.json`**, or ship-ledger from **other** dispatch bundle folders
- **`ls -lt`** (or any mtime sort) across all dispatch folders under `.sedea/operations/`
- Inferring dispatch scope from “newest” folder, parallel tabs, or PR index alone without **`targetPlanSlug`** + active **`dispatchId`**

Refresh host identity with MCP **`sedea_get_current_user`** when a skill requires it — **not** to derive operations filesystem paths.

---

## Phase-tagged storage (hybrid migration)

Operations persistence is migrating from filesystem bundles to workspace-bound RxDB/SQLite. Follow the **active phase** in Sedea rule **0** — do not mix legacy and new contracts on the same turn.

| Phase | Agent contract |
|-------|----------------|
| **Phase 0 — governance** | Filesystem bundles; scope = **`dispatchId`** + **bundle directory** + explicit plan paths from spawn **`inputs`** |
| **Hybrid** | DB-first for covered dispatch entities; filesystem fallback when entity not in workspace DB (host logs fallback — agents do not open raw DB URLs) |
| **DB-only** | Dispatch CRUD via workspace DB; no epoch-folder discovery |

During **Phase 0** and **hybrid**, the host may still resolve internal filesystem paths. That resolution is **host-internal** — agents must not document or rely on **`operationsUserId`** path segments.

---

## Plans and docs paths

| Surface | Rule |
|---------|------|
| **PR / phase plans** | Use **`targetPlanPath`**, **`parentPlanPath`**, or other explicit spawn **`inputs`** — absolute or workspace-relative paths supplied by Mission Control |
| **Follow-up edits** | Reuse the anchored absolute plan path from the lane — do not re-derive from directory segments under `.sedea/operations/` |
| **Docs reports** | Write only when a skill names the doc type; path comes from Mission Control handover or skill procedure on the **main hosting clone** |

**Path placeholders in documentation:** `` `...` `` inside path examples marks **omitted middle segments**, not a folder named `...`. Substitute the **bundle-relative** or **handover-supplied** segment — never literal **`joint`** or a user-id segment you constructed yourself.

