## Legacy CLI (`plan-state.mjs`) — hybrid only

Until Hub/CLI governance PR lands, **`plan-state.mjs`** may still accept **`--operations-user-id <id>`** for CLI-only flows without Mission Control context. On **Mission Control agent lanes**, prefer explicit plan paths from spawn **`inputs`**; do not treat the CLI flag as the primary scope contract.

**Hosting repo cwd:** **`plan-state.mjs`**, **`plan-ws-completeness.mjs`**, and **`pr-review.mjs`** run from **`HOSTING_ROOT`** — see [`.sedea/centers/research-and-development/rules/20_efficient-pr-shipping.mdc`](20_efficient-pr-shipping.mdc) § *Hosting repo cwd for scripts (canonical)*.

```bash
WORKTREE_ROOT="$(pwd)"   # hosting repo worktree (or primary hosting repo when same)
# Set HOSTING_ROOT: walk up until .sedea/centers/sedea/ or .sedea/ exists — see rule 20
cd "$HOSTING_ROOT"

node .sedea/centers/research-and-development/missions/plan-and-deliver/scripts/plan-state.mjs \
  resolve --cwd "$WORKTREE_ROOT"
```

When Mission Control supplies a plan anchor, pass that plan's absolute path to completeness and sidecar scripts via **`--file`** / spawn **`inputs`** rather than reconstructing scope from legacy user-id flags.

---

## Spawned skill outputs

If a spawned skill requires dispatch scope fields that Mission Control did not inject, return **`partial`** with `outputs.missingFields` naming the missing binding (for example `dispatchId`, `bundleDirectory`) — do not invent ids or read sibling dispatch folders to recover scope.
